[16:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on this. And that is a major bummer. So, too tall, too tall, those are eliminated. I might also work on my beer cans here. That would be really cool. But, let\'s see if this train prints.'

[16:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I brought a photo of my train into Photoshop and started editing my artwork to fit the train. You know, after doing this train, I kind of stopped doing a lot of the photo editing in Photoshop and just started doing it in the Uphie'

[16:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Make software because they have all the same tools in there and working directly with the printer\'s snapshot is more accurate than working with photos from my phone. After that, I made sure to tape up all the areas of my train where I didn\'t want any printer ink to get.'

[17:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The printer snapshot measured the train. I put the art in place and since this is a black train with writing and texture, I bumped up the layers of white all the'

[17:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way to 10 layers of white before it started printing color. I figured that would give it some really good opacity, and honestly, it was probably overkill. The printer printed the train, and when it was done, I prepped the other side'

[17:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for printing. I got my next piece of art in place and printed that, too. When it was done, I removed the tape, and this thing turned out really good, even with the black background and all the textures, this looks awesome.'

[17:45] [scene:talk]
